				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Taking Stock of the $10 Billion Washington Spent on Colombiaâs War</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Ernesto Londo&#241;o			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-11-16T16:59:52+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 16, 2015 11:59 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 16, 2015 11:59 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/11/16/taking-stock-of-the-10-billion-washington-spent-on-colombias-war/" data-title="Taking Stock of the $10 Billion Washington Spent on Colombiaâs War" data-description="The American ambassador in BogotÃ¡ discusses Colombia-U.S. relations, cocaine production and the accuracy of the show âNarcos.â">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/13/opinion/13whitakerWeb/13whitakerWeb-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/13/opinion/13whitakerWeb/13whitakerWeb-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/13/opinion/13whitakerWeb/13whitakerWeb-blog480.jpg" id="100000004035921" width="480" height="305" alt="Kevin Whitaker, the American ambassador to Colombia, right, listens to former Colombian defense ministerÂ Juan Carlos PinzÃ³n speak."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="305"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Kevin Whitaker, the American ambassador to Colombia, right, listens to former Colombian defense ministerÂ Juan Carlos PinzÃ³n speak.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> -- Guillermo Legaria/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The United States has spent more than $10 billion dollars beefing up Colombiaâs security forces, supporting development and backing reform of the judicial system in an effort known as Plan Colombia. After playing an instrumental role in giving the Colombian government the upper hand in its decades-long war against the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, a Marxist guerrilla group, Washington has turned its attention to peacemaking. I talked withÂ <a href="//bogota.usembassy.gov/ae_about_the_embassy2/the-ambassador.html">Kevin Whitaker</a>, the American ambassador in BogotÃ¡, by email about this evolution and Washingtonâs decision to sit down with leaders who are under indictment in the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>American taxpayers have spent tens of billions of dollars <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/04/world/middleeast/uss-billions-fail-to-sustain-foreign-forces.html">in largely dispiriting efforts</a> to build security forces in Iraq and Afghanistan. What did they get for the $10 billion Washington has spent in Colombia?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over the last 16 years, that nation has gone from a near-failed state, with a barracks-bound military unable to control a large, geographically segmented nation swarming with guerrillas, paramilitary groups and predatory criminal organizations, to a vibrant institutional democracy with a strong, free-market economy and powerful, capable security forces fully respectful of their civilian masters.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why has the Colombia model proved to difficult to replicate elsewhere?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even in its darkest days, Colombia enjoyed certain advantages that do not exist everywhere. Colombia has a great degree of linguistic, religious, racial, and cultural homogeneity. Colombians have a profound sense of nationhood: Even the rebels wear the Colombian flag on their sleeves. Colombia has had a functioning democracy for many decades, and the notion of civilian control of the military is well established. Perhaps the most important factor is the enduring will of the Colombian government and people to save their nation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How much of Plan Colombia, which began in the late 1990s, was financed by Colombian government?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our significant $10 billion contribution to Plan Colombia amounts to less than 5% of the total cost of that endeavor. Colombians invested in their own future. Their commitment to work collaboratively with us, and to sacrifice for their nation, was critical.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Plan Colombia, which started during the Clinton administration, had strong bipartisan support even as the White House changed hands and congressional leaders retired. Why?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You canât throw a rock in Washington without hitting three people who call themselves the father or mother of Plan Colombia. That is a profoundly good thing. The Clinton and Bush administrations wisely engaged, early and often, with Congressional leaders. The Obama administration and this Congress have remained engaged.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Earlier this year, the <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-names-aronson-special-envoy-to-colombia-1424479308?alg=y">State Departmentâs envoy</a> to the Colombian peace process, Bernard Aronson, <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-envoy-bernard-aronson-pushes-peace-in-colombia-1444422249">met with leaders of the FARC in Havana</a> to help steer along the peace process that began three years ago. Itâs rare for an American official to sit down with members of a group on the State Departmentâs terrorist list, and particularly striking considering severalÂ ofÂ <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2gLQgKLOVRY">the organizationâs leaders are under federal indictment in the United States. </a>What did these meetings accomplish?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bernie has engaged directly with the FARC to underline the historic, even unique, opportunity presented to them to negotiate an end this conflict once and for all. And heâs made clear that whatever policies they may promote, we will oppose them if they continue to use violence to achieve them. We will continue to investigate and pursue violations of American law. But if they leave that aside forever, disarm, take responsibility for their crimes, and accept justice, they have this opportunity to access Colombiaâs institutional democracy, to make their case to the Colombian people.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>FARC leaders worry that a future Colombian government could extradite them to the United States. If the Colombian government <a href="//www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/24/us-colombia-rebels-idUSKCN0RO10K20150924">makes a legally-binding commitment </a>not to do so as part of a final peace deal, would the United States object?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Extradition is a bilateral process, meaning both nations must agree.Â  On a limited number of occasions in the past, Colombia has not approved requested extraditions.Â  We respected those decisions, as we respect all sovereign decisions by Colombia. Disapproval of an extradition request does not change the fact that an indictment still exists, nor does it affect our obligation to seek to bring an individual to justice.Â We have by far the most productive extradition relationship in the world with Colombia. The nearly 2,000 extraditions of Colombians to the United States since 2002 have benefitted Colombian justice, American justice, and victims in both countries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Several FARC leaders facing drug trafficking and kidnapping charges are on the State Departmentâs <a href="//www.state.gov/j/inl/narc/rewards/c27667.htm">Narcotics Rewards Program</a>, which offers millions of dollars for information that leads to their arrest. If a peace deal is struck, will these bounties remain active or could they conceivably go away?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Rewards for Justice program exists because we continue to seek individuals indicted for violations of AmericanÂ law. This program has worked well in Colombia and in other nations. It gives us another tool to ensure that when a grand jury has determined there is probable cause that an individual has violated our laws, that individual is brought to justice. We have an obligation to ensure that those indicted for serious crimes like drug trafficking and the kidnapping of American citizens are brought to justice.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Colombian government recently decided to halt aerial spraying of drug crops,<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/15/world/americas/colombia-halts-us-backed-spraying-of-illegal-coca-crops.html"> over your objections. </a>What effect do you anticipate that will have?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Colombia made a sovereign decision based on itsÂ law to end aerial eradication with glyphosate. To address this important change, the government has formulated a new counternarcotics strategy emphasizing interdiction, manual eradication and alternative development to provide a decent living for Colombians now involved in the illegal economy. We have worked closely with them as they have formulated the new strategy, and are committed to continuing to support them in this effort.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>One of the key objectives of Plan Colombia was to fight the drug trade, and yetÂ <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/in-a-blow-to-us-policy-colombia-is-again-the-worlds-top-producer-of-coca/2015/11/10/316d2f66-7bf0-11e5-bfb6-65300a5ff562_story.html">cocaine production is booming across the country</a>. How do you explain that failure?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Without question, our efforts under Plan Colombia reduced coca and cocaine production dramatically over the life of the program. Without this combined U.S.-Colombian effort, coca production would be much higher than it is now.Â It is true that the area under coca cultivation increased by nearly 40% from 2013 to 2014. There are a number of factors at work here. The movement of coca to areas where eradication is more difficult due to legal restrictions, like national parks and indigenous reserves, is an important factor. There is substantial evidence that the FARC is encouragingÂ increased planting.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What impact do you think a peace deal could have on the narcotics industry?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The FARC is one of the most significant drugÂ trafficking organizations in the world. The linkage between a durable peace and FARC drugÂ trafficking is clear. Real peace must include greater security in rural areas and the ability to earn a decent and licit livelihood.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>There is overt, and implicit, criticism of the way the United States prosecuted the war on drugs during the 1980s and 1990s in recent television series and movies, including the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/watching-narcos-in-a-transformed-medellin.html">Netflix hit âNarcos.â </a>How much of it is deserved?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âNarcosâ is a terrific series â as is the Caracol TV series âEl Patron del Mal,â covering the same tragic period. Dramas focus on conflict, and both series show the dedication and heroism of the Colombian security forces and people. For our part, weâve recognized our responsibility as the market for much of the drug production, and that is why we are so committed to helping our Colombian partners to address the scourge of drug production and trafficking.</p>
	</div>
